# Error Handling

## Backend (NestJS)

Use NestJS built-in exceptions with meaningful messages:

```typescript
// Good: specific exception with context
throw new NotFoundException(`Tournament ${id} not found`);
throw new BadRequestException("Bet amount exceeds stack size");
throw new ConflictException("Bot already registered for this tournament");

// Bad: generic errors
throw new Error("Not found");
throw new HttpException("Error", 400);
```

The `HttpExceptionFilter` transforms these into user-friendly responses automatically.

### Async Operations

Always handle errors in async code:

```typescript
// Service method
async processAction(gameId: string, action: Action): Promise<void> {
  const game = await this.gameRepo.findById(gameId);
  if (!game) {
    throw new NotFoundException(`Game ${gameId} not found`);
  }
  // ... business logic
}
```

### External Service Calls (Bots)

Wrap with timeout and specific error handling:

```typescript
try {
  const response = await this.httpService.axiosRef.post(bot.endpoint, payload, {
    timeout: this.config.botTimeoutMs,
  });
  return response.data;
} catch (error) {
  if (error.code === "ECONNABORTED") {
    throw new GatewayTimeoutException(`Bot ${bot.id} timed out`);
  }
  throw new ServiceUnavailableException(`Bot ${bot.id} unreachable`);
}
```

## Frontend (React)

### API Calls in Stores

```typescript
fetchTournament: async (id) => {
  set({ loading: true, error: null });
  try {
    const tournament = await api.getById(id);
    set({ currentTournament: tournament, loading: false });
  } catch (error) {
    set({ error: String(error), loading: false });
  }
},
```

### Display Errors to Users

```tsx
const { error, clearError } = useTournamentStore();

{error && (
  <div className="bg-red-500/10 text-red-400 p-4 rounded">
    {error}
    <button onClick={clearError}>Dismiss</button>
  </div>
)}
```

### Use ErrorBoundary for Crashes

Wrap feature sections to prevent full-page crashes:

```tsx
<ErrorBoundary>
  <GameView />
</ErrorBoundary>
```

## Logging

Use the logger with context:

```typescript
// Backend
this.logger.error(`Failed to process action`, error.stack);

// Frontend
logger.error("Failed to fetch data", error, "TournamentStore", { id });
```
